{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513383"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:09:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:09:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12104"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12104"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.19,0.11,0.12,0.47]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4649"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102731"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4649"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12104"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85214"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"763"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7075"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7797"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15058"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36042"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42707"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44534"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102731"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 39-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department of a small rural hospital with a 24-hour history of increasing pain in his right groin. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. Recently, he has noticed a lump in his right groin, which usually only appears when he stands up, but has been persistent for the last day. He does not smoke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 134/84 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.6\u00b0C. His BMI is 29 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. His abdomen is soft and normal, apart from a clearly visible 4 cm swelling immediately superomedial to the right pubic tubercle. The swelling is erythematous, tender and appears to be fixed when pressed.. There is no cough impulse.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Manually reduce the swelling","Ultrasound","CT abdomen and pelvis","Laparoscopy","Surgical exploration"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features consistent with a strangulated inguinal hernia. The description of the site of the mass, immediately superomedial to the right pubic tubercle, is characteristic of an inguinal hernia. The hernia is incarcerated (cannot be reduced) and likely strangulated, as evidenced by the acute pain, erythema over the swelling, and tenderness to palpation. The absence of a cough impulse further supports that the hernia is incarcerated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical exploration\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management. Prompt surgical intervention is necessary as there is likely a loop or section of small bowel trapped within the hernial sac (Image). If addressed early, the bowel may still be viable, potentially avoiding the need for a formal laparotomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EManually reduce the swelling\u003C/strong\u003E should not be attempted in cases of suspected strangulation due to the risk of bowel perforation and/or introduction of necrotic bowel into the abdominal cavity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful in distinguishing an irreducible or strangulated hernia from other causes of groin swelling, such as enlarged lymph nodes. However, in this case, the diagnosis is clinically apparent, and an ultrasound is unlikely to change management. Moreover, a small rural hospital may not have the facilities or personnel skilled in emergency abdominal ultrasonography.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E may be used to diagnose difficult-to-assess groin hernias, but would be unlikely to change management in this case where the diagnosis is already clinically apparent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered in cases of incarceration, but this case has progressed beyond mere irreducibility. Strangulation is an absolute contraindication to laparoscopic repair of groin hernias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the priority in managing a strangulated inguinal hernia is prompt surgical exploration to assess bowel viability and prevent further complications such as bowel necrosis or perforation. Other diagnostic modalities should not delay definitive surgical management when the clinical presentation is clear.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In the surgical management of groin hernias, strangulation is an absolute contraindication to laparoscopic repair.","Strangulated inguinal hernias require prompt surgical exploration to assess bowel viability and prevent complications.","Manual reduction of a strangulated hernia should not be attempted due to the risk of bowel perforation or introduction of necrotic bowel into the abdominal cavity."],"references":["Turner RC. A general practitioner primer on groin hernias. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2018 Aug;47(8):530-3. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2018/august/general-practitioner-primer-on-groin-hernias","Burkhardt JH, Arshanskiy Y, Munson JL, Scholz FJ. Diagnosis of inguinal region hernias with axial CT: the lateral crescent sign and other key findings. Radiographics. 2011 Mar;31(2):E1-2. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21415178/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85214"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12104"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20027"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20027"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d8106905-1d53-42f0-a9bd-f67b0a89d86a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d8106905-1d53-42f0-a9bd-f67b0a89d86a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85214"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-15T08:35:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-15T08:38:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4649"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102731"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergen